(c) Multiple linear regression

lm.fit <- lm(mpg~.,data = Auto[colnames(Auto) != "name"])
summary(lm.fit)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = mpg ~ ., data = Auto[colnames(Auto) != "name"])

## horsepower    -0.016951   0.013787  -1.230  0.21963

## Residual standard error: 3.328 on 384 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.8215, Adjusted R-squared:  0.8182 
## F-statistic: 252.4 on 7 and 384 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
  1. From the overall R-square and p-value, there is a relationship between the predictors and the response.
  2. Displacement, weight, year and origin are predictors with a statistically significant relationship to the response.
  3. The coefficient for year is 0.750773, which suggests that newer cars tend to have higher mpg.

(d) Disgnostic plots

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(lm.fit)

  • The Q-Q plot actually shows that there are some unusually large outliers.
  • The residual-vs-leverage plot shows that all residuals have low Cook’s distance, with only one point having relatively high leverage.
